      <h1>How Many Calories Should You Eat to Lose Weight?</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">One of the most common questions in health and fitness is deceptively simple: how many calories do I need to eat to lose weight? The answer is different for every person because it depends on your metabolism, body composition, activity level, and goals. But the underlying science is straightforward. Weight loss comes down to energy balance, and once you understand how to calculate your personal calorie needs and create a sustainable deficit, you can lose weight safely and keep it off. This guide walks you through the concepts of TDEE and BMR, shows you how to calculate your numbers, explains safe minimums, and offers practical advice for when progress stalls.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <section>
      <h2>The Energy Balance Equation</h2>
      <p>At its core, weight management is governed by energy balance. Your body takes in energy through food and expends energy through metabolic processes, physical activity, and digestion. When you consume more calories than you burn, the excess energy is stored, primarily as body fat. When you consume fewer calories than you burn, your body taps into stored energy to make up the difference, resulting in weight loss. This is not an oversimplification or a controversial claim. It is a fundamental principle of thermodynamics that has been confirmed by hundreds of metabolic research studies over the past century.</p>
      <p>That said, energy balance is not the whole story. The types of foods you eat, your hormonal environment, sleep quality, stress levels, and genetic factors all influence how efficiently your body processes calories and how hungry or satisfied you feel on a given intake. Two people eating the same number of calories may have different experiences with hunger, energy, and body composition. But the energy balance equation remains the foundation upon which all weight loss strategies are built. If you are not in a calorie deficit, you will not lose body fat regardless of what foods you eat or what diet label you follow.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Understanding Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)</h2>
      <p>Your Basal Metabolic Rate is the number of calories your body burns at complete rest just to keep you alive. This includes the energy required to maintain your heart beating, your lungs breathing, your brain functioning, your cells regenerating, and your organs operating. For most people, BMR accounts for 60 to 75 percent of total daily calorie expenditure, making it by far the largest component of your energy budget.</p>
      <p>BMR is influenced by several factors you cannot change, including age (BMR decreases roughly two percent per decade after age 20), sex (men generally have higher BMRs due to greater muscle mass), height, and genetics. It is also influenced by factors you can modify, particularly your lean body mass. Muscle tissue is more metabolically active than fat tissue, which is one reason strength training is beneficial for weight management.</p>

      <h3>The Mifflin-St Jeor Equation</h3>
      <p>The Mifflin-St Jeor equation, published in 1990, is widely considered the most accurate BMR estimation formula for most adults. It calculates BMR as follows. For men: BMR = (10 x weight in kg) + (6.25 x height in cm) - (5 x age in years) + 5. For women: BMR = (10 x weight in kg) + (6.25 x height in cm) - (5 x age in years) - 161. For example, a 35-year-old woman who weighs 70 kg and is 165 cm tall would have an estimated BMR of (10 x 70) + (6.25 x 165) - (5 x 35) - 161 = 700 + 1031 - 175 - 161 = 1,395 calories per day.</p>

      <h3>The Harris-Benedict Equation</h3>
      <p>The original Harris-Benedict equation was developed in 1919 and revised in 1984 by Roza and Shizgal. While still widely referenced, studies have shown it tends to overestimate BMR by about five percent compared to the Mifflin-St Jeor equation. For men: BMR = 88.362 + (13.397 x weight in kg) + (4.799 x height in cm) - (5.677 x age in years). For women: BMR = 447.593 + (9.247 x weight in kg) + (3.098 x height in cm) - (4.330 x age in years). You can use our <a href="/health-calculators/bmr-calculator/">BMR calculator</a> to quickly compute your number using either formula.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>From BMR to TDEE: Activity Multipliers</h2>
      <p>Your Total Daily Energy Expenditure is what you actually burn in a full day, including all movement and activity on top of your BMR. To estimate TDEE, you multiply your BMR by an activity factor that reflects your typical daily movement patterns. The standard activity multipliers are as follows.</p>
      <p>Sedentary (little or no exercise, desk job): BMR x 1.2. Lightly active (light exercise one to three days per week): BMR x 1.375. Moderately active (moderate exercise three to five days per week): BMR x 1.55. Very active (hard exercise six to seven days per week): BMR x 1.725. Extremely active (very hard exercise, physical job, or training twice per day): BMR x 1.9.</p>
      <p>Using our earlier example, if the 35-year-old woman with a BMR of 1,395 calories exercises moderately three to five times per week, her estimated TDEE would be 1,395 x 1.55 = approximately 2,162 calories per day. This is the number of calories she would need to eat each day to maintain her current weight. To lose weight, she would need to eat fewer calories than this number.</p>
      <p>It is worth noting that most people overestimate their activity level. Unless you have a physically demanding job or are training intensely most days of the week, starting with the sedentary or lightly active multiplier is often more accurate. You can always adjust based on your results over the first few weeks.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The 500-Calorie Deficit Rule</h2>
      <p>A widely cited guideline states that a daily calorie deficit of 500 calories leads to approximately one pound (0.45 kg) of weight loss per week. This is based on the approximation that one pound of body fat contains about 3,500 calories of stored energy, so a deficit of 500 calories per day over seven days equals 3,500 calories, or one pound of fat. While newer research suggests the relationship is not perfectly linear because your metabolism adapts over time, the 500-calorie rule remains a useful and practical starting point for most people.</p>
      <p>For a more aggressive but still safe rate of loss, a deficit of 750 to 1,000 calories per day can produce weight loss of 1.5 to 2 pounds per week. However, larger deficits are harder to sustain, increase the risk of muscle loss, and may lead to greater metabolic adaptation. For most people, a deficit of 500 to 750 calories per day strikes the best balance between meaningful progress and sustainability. Research consistently shows that people who lose weight at a moderate pace are more likely to keep it off long-term than those who pursue rapid weight loss.</p>
      <p>Returning to our example, the woman with a TDEE of 2,162 calories would aim for approximately 1,662 calories per day to lose about one pound per week, or about 1,412 calories per day to lose 1.5 pounds per week. These are realistic, sustainable targets that keep her well above the minimum recommended intake.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Minimum Safe Calorie Intake</h2>
      <p>While creating a calorie deficit is necessary for weight loss, there is a floor below which cutting calories becomes counterproductive and potentially dangerous. Most nutrition and medical organizations recommend that women consume no fewer than 1,200 calories per day and men consume no fewer than 1,500 calories per day without medical supervision. These minimums are based on the difficulty of meeting essential nutrient needs at very low calorie levels.</p>
      <p>Eating too few calories triggers a cascade of negative effects. Your body begins to break down muscle tissue for energy, which lowers your metabolic rate and makes future weight loss harder. Essential nutrient intake becomes insufficient, increasing the risk of deficiencies in iron, calcium, B vitamins, and other critical micronutrients. Energy levels plummet, cognitive function declines, immune function is compromised, and hormonal disruptions can occur, including changes to thyroid function and reproductive hormones. Very low calorie diets also tend to increase cortisol levels, which promotes fat storage particularly around the midsection.</p>
      <p>Perhaps most importantly, extreme calorie restriction is psychologically unsustainable and is strongly associated with binge eating episodes, an unhealthy relationship with food, and weight cycling (repeated loss and regain). If your calculated calorie target falls below the recommended minimums, the better approach is to increase your physical activity to create a larger deficit while eating an adequate amount, or to accept a slower rate of weight loss.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to Calculate Your Personal Number</h2>
      <p>Putting it all together, here is a step-by-step process for determining how many calories you should eat to lose weight. Step one: calculate your BMR using the Mifflin-St Jeor equation or use our <a href="/health-calculators/bmr-calculator/">BMR calculator</a>. Step two: multiply your BMR by the appropriate activity factor to estimate your TDEE. Step three: subtract 500 to 750 calories from your TDEE to determine your daily calorie target for weight loss. Step four: check that your target does not fall below 1,200 calories for women or 1,500 calories for men. Step five: use our <a href="/health-calculators/calorie-calculator/">calorie calculator</a> to verify your numbers and explore different scenarios.</p>
      <p>Once you have your number, the next step is tracking your intake for at least two to four weeks to see how your body responds. Weigh yourself at the same time each day, preferably in the morning before eating, and use a weekly average rather than daily readings to smooth out normal fluctuations from water retention, sodium intake, and digestive contents. If you are losing weight at your target rate, your numbers are working. If you are losing too quickly or too slowly, adjust your calorie target by 100 to 200 calories and reassess after another two weeks.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Breaking Through Weight Loss Plateaus</h2>
      <p>Almost everyone who pursues sustained weight loss will encounter a plateau, a period of several weeks where the scale stops moving despite consistent effort. Plateaus are frustrating but entirely normal, and understanding why they happen makes them much easier to overcome.</p>
      <p>The primary cause of plateaus is that your calorie needs decrease as you lose weight. A smaller body burns fewer calories at rest and during activity. The deficit that produced steady weight loss at your starting weight may no longer be a deficit at your current weight. The solution is to recalculate your TDEE at your new weight and adjust your calorie target accordingly.</p>
      <p>Metabolic adaptation is another factor. Research shows that prolonged calorie restriction can reduce your metabolic rate beyond what would be predicted by weight loss alone, a phenomenon sometimes called adaptive thermogenesis. Your body becomes more efficient at using energy, and you may unconsciously reduce non-exercise activity like fidgeting, standing, and walking. This adaptation is modest, typically amounting to 50 to 100 calories per day, but it contributes to plateaus over time.</p>
      <p>Before adjusting your approach, first ensure you are tracking your intake accurately. Studies consistently find that people underestimate their calorie intake by 20 to 50 percent, even when actively trying to track. Common sources of untracked calories include cooking oils, condiments, beverages, and underestimating portion sizes. Using a food scale for at least a few days can reveal surprising discrepancies.</p>
      <p>Strategies for breaking through a plateau include recalculating your TDEE at your current weight, adding strength training to preserve or build muscle mass, increasing daily non-exercise activity such as walking, taking a brief diet break of one to two weeks at maintenance calories to reduce metabolic adaptation, and ensuring adequate sleep and stress management, both of which significantly affect hormones that regulate hunger and fat storage.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Sustainable Weight Loss Strategies</h2>
      <p>Knowing your calorie target is only the beginning. Long-term success depends on building sustainable habits that allow you to maintain a calorie deficit without feeling deprived, hungry, or miserable. Research on successful long-term weight loss consistently highlights several key strategies.</p>
      <p>Prioritize protein intake. Protein is the most satiating macronutrient, meaning it keeps you feeling full longer per calorie consumed. It also has the highest thermic effect of food, meaning your body burns more calories digesting protein than carbohydrates or fat. Aiming for 0.7 to 1 gram of protein per pound of body weight helps preserve muscle mass during weight loss and reduces hunger. Good sources include lean meats, fish, eggs, dairy, legumes, and tofu.</p>
      <p>Eat plenty of fiber-rich foods. Vegetables, fruits, whole grains, and legumes are high in fiber, which slows digestion, promotes satiety, and supports gut health. These foods also tend to be high in volume and low in calorie density, meaning you can eat large, satisfying portions without consuming excessive calories. Research suggests that simply increasing fiber intake to 30 grams per day can produce meaningful weight loss even without other dietary changes.</p>
      <p>Plan and prepare meals in advance. Decision fatigue and lack of preparation are among the most common reasons people abandon their calorie goals. Having healthy meals and snacks readily available dramatically reduces the likelihood of impulsive, high-calorie choices. Even basic meal preparation, such as cooking proteins and grains in batches at the start of the week, can make a significant difference in adherence.</p>
      <p>Allow flexibility. Rigid, all-or-nothing approaches to dieting are consistently associated with worse long-term outcomes compared to flexible approaches that allow for occasional treats and social meals without guilt. The goal is progress over time, not perfection every day. A sustainable plan is one you can follow 80 to 90 percent of the time while still enjoying your life.</p>
    </section>

