    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How many calories should I eat per day to lose weight?</summary>
        <p>The number depends on your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE). Most people can lose about one pound per week by eating 500 fewer calories than their TDEE. For many adults, this translates to 1,200 to 1,800 calories per day, but the exact figure varies based on age, sex, height, weight, and activity level. Use our <a href="/health-calculators/calorie-calculator/">calorie calculator</a> to find your personal number.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the minimum number of calories you should eat?</summary>
        <p>Most health professionals recommend that women eat no fewer than 1,200 calories per day and men no fewer than 1,500 calories per day without medical supervision. Going below these levels makes it difficult to get adequate nutrition and can lead to muscle loss, metabolic slowdown, fatigue, and other health problems. Very low calorie diets should only be followed under direct medical supervision.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is TDEE and how do I calculate it?</summary>
        <p>TDEE stands for Total Daily Energy Expenditure and represents all the calories your body burns in a day, including your basal metabolic rate, digestion, and physical activity. Calculate it by first finding your BMR using a formula like Mifflin-St Jeor, then multiplying by an activity factor (1.2 for sedentary up to 1.9 for extremely active). Your TDEE is the calorie intake needed to maintain your current weight. Subtract 500 for roughly one pound of loss per week.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why have I stopped losing weight even though I am eating fewer calories?</summary>
        <p>Weight loss plateaus happen because your calorie needs decrease as you lose weight, your metabolism may adapt to prolonged restriction, and calorie tracking often becomes less accurate over time. To break through, recalculate your TDEE at your new weight, verify your tracking accuracy with a food scale, consider increasing physical activity, and ensure you are getting enough sleep and managing stress.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is it better to cut calories or exercise more for weight loss?</summary>
        <p>Diet-based calorie reduction is generally more effective for creating a deficit, since it is much easier to cut 500 calories from food than to burn 500 extra calories through exercise. However, combining both approaches produces the best results. Exercise preserves muscle mass, improves metabolic health, and is one of the strongest predictors of long-term weight maintenance. A moderate calorie reduction paired with regular physical activity is the ideal strategy.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

